<BLOCK1><TI>APPLICANTS SUBMISSIONS</TI>
<P>1] I first filed on May 5<SUP>th</SUP>, 2014 to start the proceeding. I spent approximately 1 hour there trying to understand all the procedures that followed and timelines as I am new to this</P>
<P>I was told by one of the staff at the counter that first I was to for 30 days, for them to respond and once received I had 20/30 days to send an affidavit to them, which i did, by courier or registered mail. I did this on June 19<SUP>th</SUP> and did not get their response till near the end of 30 days of applying Then I was told I had to wait till they received it and file proof of service within 20 days of them receiving it.</P>
<P>This is the procedure I followed and hence I arrived at the court office to file the proof of service on July 7th, 2014. Given what I was told this was bang on within the time frame</P>
<P>I then received in the mail a day later, the returned proof of service telling me I filed too late and have to file a request for extension.</P>
<P>Hence what I am doing now.</P>
<P>I have to say I am very frustrated because I followed what I thought I was told to do and now find out I was given apparently wrong info. I did not file late because of being tardy I followed what I thought was the correct procedure and time limits.</P>
<P>2] This was very frustrating as I spent a good hour in the office with someone explaining what I had to do.</P>
<P>But either way it would have been impossible for me to serve my affidavit and proof of service within 30 days after the application even had I been explained the procedure properly or understood it properly.</P>
<P>By the time I received the respondents response, to my application 30 days was almost up. So how could I or any normal person read through their massively huge response, type a response in an affidavit and gather needed evidence to support it[exhibits] get it commissioned and then serve it and then wait till you can get proof you served it and then come down to your office and file proof of service, all in 30 days? This would have been absolutely impossible and even the agent whom called me today[July 9th/14, acknowledged that they can see that this would have been impossible and went on to explain how I could have applied at that time for an extension agreement with the other party. But that is also too late now.</P>
<P>Very frustrating.</P>
<P>I appreciate the courts understanding this and granting an extension to file. I had Already filed and have the paper work ready.</P>
<P>Thanks</P>
<P>&ellip35; SCOTT ROBINSON</P>
